{"title_page": "Vanesa Gottifredi", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine chemist and biologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Vanesa Gottifredi\n| image           = Vanesa Gottifredi (mincyt).jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1969|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Salta Province]], Argentina\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| death_cause     = \n| other_names     = \n| occupation      = \n| spouse          = \n| children        = \n| awards          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bernardo Houssay Award]] (2014)\n* [[L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO For Women in Science Awards|L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO Award]] (2019)\n}}\n| education       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[National University of Salta]]\n* [[Sapienza University of Rome]]\n}}\n| website         = \n}}\n'''Vanesa Gottifredi''' (born 13 November 1969) is an Argentine chemist and biologist. She works as a researcher in the Principal Investigator category of the Scientific and Technological Researcher Program (CICT) of the [[National Scientific and Technical Research Council]] (CONICET). She is also head of the [[Leloir Institute]]'s Cell Cycle and Genomic Stability Laboratory. She specializes in the mechanisms of [[tumor]] cell response to [[chemotherapy]], work for which she was awarded by the [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO For Women in Science Awards|L'Oreal-UNESCO]].\n\n==Career==\nVanesa Gottifredi completed her undergraduate studies at the [[National University of Salta]], where she obtained a [[Licentiate (degree)#Argentina|licentiate]] in chemistry in 1992. She then studied at the [[Sapienza University of Rome]], where she graduated as a doctor in [[human biology]] in 1998.<ref name=busca>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/cientificas-argentinas-lideran-investigaciones-entender-propaga-cancer_0_BkLpoMLaW.html |title=En busca de nuevos blancos terap\u00e9uticos |trans-title=In Search of New Therapeutic Targets |first=Rosario |last=Medina |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |language=Spanish |date=2017-10-19 |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Later she conducted postdoctoral studies in [[cell biology]] and [[cancer]] at [[Columbia University]] in the United States.\n\nAs head of the Cell Cycle and Genomic Stability Laboratory at the [[Leloir Institute|Leloir Institute Foundation]], she conducts research on defense mechanisms that both normal and tumor cells use to cope with adverse events, and how malignant cells avoid the effects of [[chemotherapy]].<ref name=busca/><ref name=Rosada>{{Cite web |url=https://www.casarosada.gob.ar/informacion/actividad-oficial/9-noticias/40291-una-cientifica-argentina-recibio-premio-de-fundacion-von-humboldt |title=Una cient\u00edfica argentina recibi\u00f3 premio de fundaci\u00f3n Von Humboldt |trans-title=An Argentine Scientist Receives Award from Von Humboldt Foundation |publisher=[[President of Argentina|Office of the President of Argentina]] |language=Spanish |date=2017-08-10 |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Special mention for the L\u00f3re\u00e1l-UNESCO Award, 2013\n* [[Bernardo Houssay Award]] for Medical Science, 2014<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.argentina.gob.ar/ciencia/ganadores/premios-houssay-2014 |title=Premios Houssay |trans-title=Houssay Awards |publisher=[[Ministry of Science, Technology and Productive Innovation]] |language=Spanish |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel Award from the [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]], 2017<ref name=Rosada/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.conicet.gov.ar/premian-a-cientifica-del-conicet-que-estudia-como-las-celulas-malignas-evaden-el-ataque-de-la-quimioterapia/ |title=Premian a cient\u00edfica del CONICET que estudia c\u00f3mo las c\u00e9lulas malignas evaden el ataque de la quimioterapia |trans-title=CONICET Scientist Awarded for Showing How Malignant Cells Evade the Attack of Chemotherapy |publisher=[[National Scientific and Technical Research Council]] |language=Spanish |date=2017-08-09 |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* Ben Barres Spotlight Award from ''[[eLife]]'', 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://elifesciences.org/inside-elife/17433d27/ben-barres-spotlight-awards-announcing-the-winners |title=Ben Barres Spotlight Awards: Announcing the winners |first=Kora |last=Korzec |work=[[eLife]] |date=2019-08-28 |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* [[L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO For Women in Science Awards|L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO For Women in Science Award]] (Argentine national edition), in collaboration with CONICET, 2019<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/investiga-celulas-cancer-escapan-quimioterapia-gano-premio-l-oreal-unesco_0_0Xc2YrrQ.html |title=Investiga c\u00f3mo las c\u00e9lulas del c\u00e1ncer le escapan a la quimioterapia y gan\u00f3 el premio L'Oreal-Unesco |trans-title=Investigates How Cancer Cells Escape Chemotherapy and Wins the L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO Award |first=Vanesa |last=L\u00f3pez |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |language=Spanish |date=2019-10-01 |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.argentina.gob.ar/noticias/se-entregaron-los-premios-loreal-unesco-por-las-mujeres-en-la-ciencia |title=Se entregaron los Premios L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO 'Por las mujeres en la ciencia' |trans-title=L'Oreal-UNESCO 'For Women in Science' Awards Presented |publisher=[[Ministry of Science, Technology and Productive Innovation]] |language=Spanish |date=2019-03-01 |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.leloir.org.ar/gottifredi-en/ Vanesa Gottifredi] at the [[Leloir Institute]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gottifredi, Vanesa}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Argentine biologists]]\n[[Category:Argentine chemists]]\n[[Category:Argentine women scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Salta Province]]\n[[Category:Sapienza University of Rome alumni]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:Women chemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine chemist and biologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Vanesa Gottifredi\n| image           = Vanesa Gottifredi (mincyt).jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1969|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Salta Province]], Argentina\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| death_cause     = \n| other_names     = \n| occupation      = \n| spouse          = \n| children        = \n| awards          = {{Plainlist|\n* {{ill|Bernardo Houssay Award|es|Premio Bernardo Houssay|lt=Houssay Award}} (2014)\n* [[L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO For Women in Science Awards|L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO Award]] (2019)\n}}\n| education       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[National University of Salta]]\n* [[Sapienza University of Rome]]\n}}\n| website         = \n}}\n'''Vanesa Gottifredi''' (born 13 November 1969) is an Argentine chemist and biologist. She works as a researcher in the Principal Investigator category of the Scientific and Technological Researcher Program (CICT) of the [[National Scientific and Technical Research Council]] (CONICET). She is also head of the [[Leloir Institute]]'s Cell Cycle and Genomic Stability Laboratory. She specializes in the mechanisms of [[tumor]] cell response to [[chemotherapy]], work for which she was awarded by the [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO For Women in Science Awards|L'Oreal-UNESCO]].\n\n==Career==\nVanesa Gottifredi completed her undergraduate studies at the [[National University of Salta]], where she obtained a [[Licentiate (degree)#Argentina|licentiate]] in chemistry in 1992. She then studied at the [[Sapienza University of Rome]], where she graduated as a doctor in [[human biology]] in 1998.<ref name=busca>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarin.com/socieda